reviewText: With today's vocal synthesized phony vocalists it is good to know that captured on film is Tom Jones. A man that could take all the manufactured singers of today out behind the barn for a butt whoopin on how to sing.There are historic magic moments caught on this DVD that will sadly never be again and if anyone can listen to the heartfelt power of Tom's voice and not be impressed then you are deaf and need a heart transplant.

reviewText: I would have loved for it to be complete episodes but I must say that I have really enjoyed this set. The "What's New Pussycat" version seen here is so nostalgic, I loved it, and The Bee Gees performance of "I Started A Joke" is priceless. Just about every performance (except for the Cass Elliot/Tom Jones medley) seem to be complete so I don't really understand the complaints. So if you are a nostalgic person (like me) you will really enjoy this set and at the current price that is going even much more.
summary: The Nostalgia Alone Makes It Worthwhile

reviewText: This is nice to have along with previous releases but why are the three shows featured only partial.There is plenty of room on the disc to include the full uncut episodes. Even allowing for licensing issues with certain guest artists,there is no excuse for excluding half of Tom's performances (whilst including guest slots with no involvement from Tom).
summary: Tom Jones  Whats New Pussycat DVD

reviewText: Let's assume that clearing nearly 40 year old material for such a project is very complicated and often leads to disappointment for all involved. Why two Tim Conway sketches, when one, would suffice?: the funny, though overlong lampoon of a News Anchor having to report the news and make a sudden adjustment to new technology - which doesn't work. Why three Ace Trucking Company sketches? Well, all three are excellent. We get two good Bee Gees songs, introduced by the fiance of one Brother. Her name is Lulu. Does she sing? No. At least she gets out a declarative sentence or two - Shirley Bassey is seen for about 1.5 seconds in an opening credit snippet. Folks, don't get your hopes up here, either. I really doubt that someone said, let's cut Bassey so we can include both Conway sketches.Point is, we gotta take what can get. Hope that the next edition has more of what we want.Yes, Tom Jones is the star, and for TJ fans there's little to complain about. He does live versions of "What'd I Say?" and "Money (That's What I Want)" which make the 14.99 seem quite superfluous. In a brilliantly designed production number, he does a brilliant "Dock Of The Bay". "Gentle On My Mind" is another fine arrangement with a sensitive vocal. On these standards he delivers mightily.As another reviewer said, man, if possible put all the This Is Tom Jones! shows in one box and charge me 99.99! (I made up the price).Can't wait for the next edition. Thanks, Time-Life.

reviewText: Instead of crying about what ISN'T on this DVD like the other reviewers, that for the most part obviously have no idea about copyrights and license issues which often preclude DVD release of previously aired material, I'll review what we DO have on this DVD.I paid $10 today at Fry's and there was quite a few items that on their own made the purchase worth it..John Denver playing a 12 string acoustic and singing James Taylor's "Carolina In My Mind"...Lulu gushing about Maurice Gibb (her fiancee) then the Bee Gees performance! The pre-hippy dippy George Carlin doing his "corporate" stand up!  Mamma Cass (always sensational) singing with Tom,  and what have I forgot...oh yeah...TONS of TOM...dancing , singing and  strutting his stuff...So..instead of crying about NOT having the Dave Clark Five (who's own records are currently out of print due to legal hassles)...and others I'll just say I'm thrilled with my ten dollars spent and this trip back to the end of the sixties and early seventies!
summary: for TEN bucks this is a KILLER hour plus of Pop music history!
